@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------- Expression syntax -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "Expression syntax"
@{U}7) Expression syntax@{UU}

   Besides the usual evaluation  of expression, Laplace  now offers some  pro-
gramming facilities. The syntax is quite  similar to the C language,  although
there are some differences.

   Expressions are separated by semicolons  @{B};@{UB}. Expressions can be enclosed  in
curly braces @{B}{@{UB}, @{B}}@{UB}, e.g. to have more than one expression in a @{B}while@{UB}-loop.

   Compared to C,  Laplace works a  bit @{I}functional @{UI},  this means almost  every
statement gives you a result, even without an assignment, @{B}result(...)@{UB} or some-
thing similar. The result of an  expression block is the last expression.  You
can also abandon the execution of a block using the @{"break()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-BREAK"}-function; the  op-
tional argument is the result of the block.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} { pi; 2+3; 3i }
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}3i@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} { pi; break(2+3); 3i }
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}5@{UI}

   @{" * " LINK "Comments"}  Comments
   @{" * " LINK "Expressions"}  Expressions
   @{" * " LINK "References"}  References
   @{" * " LINK "Types"}  Types
   @{" * " LINK "Loops"}  Loops
   @{" * " LINK "Procedures"}  Procedures
   @{" * " LINK "Options"}  Options


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Comments"
@TITLE "Comments"
@NEXT "Expressions"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------------- Comments -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "Comments"
@{U}7.1) Comments@{UU}

   Laplace uses C like  comments. Everything enclosed in  @{B}/*@{UB} and @{B}*/@{UB} is  simply
ignored. Nesting is not allowed, as you know it from any C compiler.

   C++ style comments are also  recognized. After @{B}//@{UB} the  rest of the line  is
ignored (note that this is the  only case where Laplace distinguishes  between
spaces and line breaks).


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Expressions"
@TITLE "Expressions"
@NEXT "References"
@PREV "Comments"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------- Expressions -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "Expressions"
@{U}7.2) Expressions@{UU}

   Expressions are entered in a usual manner, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} 1+2/3*(4-2) @{B}<return>@{UB}

   Guess what's the result...

   More formally, an correct expression is:

 @{B}·@{UB} an object (see @{"types" LINK "Types"}) or
 @{B}·@{UB} a reference (see @{"references" LINK "References"}) or
 @{B}·@{UB} an built-in function (see @{"functions" LINK "Functions.guide/Functions"}) or
 @{B}·@{UB} expression @{B}binary_operator@{UB} expression
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}unary_operator@{UB} expression
 @{B}·@{UB} expression @{B}relation@{UB} expression

   There are the following @{B}binary operators@{UB}:

   @{B}+@{UB}         - add                  @{B}-@{UB}         - substrac
   @{B}*@{UB}         - multiply             @{B}/@{UB}         - divide
   @{B}^@{UB}         - power of             @{B}×@{UB}, @{B}cross@{UB}  - vector product
   @{B}||@{UB}, @{B}or@{UB}    - logical or           @{B}!||@{UB}, @{B}nor@{UB}  - logical nor
   @{B}&&@{UB}, @{B}and@{UB}   - logical and          @{B}!&&@{UB}, @{B}nand@{UB} - logical nand
   @{B}^^@{UB}        - logical xor          @{B}union@{UB}     - set union
   @{B}intersect@{UB} - set intersect        @{B}setminus@{UB}  - set minus

   Note: the vector product @{B}×@{UB} is not a usual x, and can be entered by @{B}alt x@{UB}.

   Further more, here are the @{B}unary operators@{UB}:

   @{B}-@{UB} - negative        @{B}!@{UB}, @{B}not@{UB} - logical not

   A @{B}relations@{UB} always results in a boolean value (@{B}TRUE@{UB} or @{B}FALSE@{UB}). This is  the
list of all relations:

   @{B}==@{UB} - equal               @{B}!=@{UB} - not equal
   @{B}<@{UB}  - less than           @{B}<=@{UB} - less or equal
   @{B}>@{UB}  - greater than        @{B}>=@{UB} - greater or equal


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "References"
@TITLE "References"
@NEXT "Types"
@PREV "Expressions"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------------ References -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "References"
@{U}7.3) References@{UU}

   If you  want to  use  an result  later or  just  define a  variable,  write
@{I}name = expression @{UI}.  This creates an  objects that can  be referenced by  it's
name in later(!) entries. If you reference to an object, Laplace searches from
the actual entry backwards,  thereby you may define  an object several  times,
but only the latest version is used. E.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} [1] a=1/2 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} [2] 2*a @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}gets @{I}a @{UI} from [1]@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} [3] a=a+1 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}@{I}a @{UI} on the right side references to the definition in [1]@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}and creates a new object called @{I}a @{UI} to be referenced below@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} [4] a @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}gets @{I}a @{UI} from [3]@{UI}

   If you move back to [2], you still get the same result, because the new @{I}a @{UI}
is defined below and cannot be reference from [2].


   You may overwrite built-in functions like @{I}sin () @{UI}, @{I}exp () @{UI} etc. and the in-
ternal constants e@{I} @{UI}  and pi@{I} @{UI}. On  the other hand,  the following keywords are
forbidden: @{B}if@{UB}, @{B}else@{UB}, @{B}while@{UB}, @{B}for@{UB} and all @{"options" LINK "Options"} (names starting with @{B}$@{UB}).


   If Laplace encounters an object name  that was not defined earlier, a  con-
stant will be automatically created:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x) = x^2 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(a) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}a^2@{UI}

   This is the same as
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x) = x^2 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} const a @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(a) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}a^2@{UI}

   This work only for number constants. If you require e.g. a constant  vector
object, you have to use the @{B}const@{UB} keyword to declare it.

   Generally you should always declare constants with @{B}const@{UB}, otherwise you are
in danger that the reference has already been defined (e.g. in a library file)
and you get a type error, look at this:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a=[1,2]
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ....
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} @{I}[thousands of lines...]@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ....
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x)=x^2
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(a)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} => @{B}error: @{UB}@{I}Not defined to vectors.@{UI}

@{U}Conventions@{UU}

   There are some special conventions  for object names. Valid characters  are
@{B}A@{UB}...@{B}Z@{UB}, @{B}Ö@{UB}, @{B}Ä@{UB}, @{B}Ü@{UB}, @{B}a@{UB}...@{B}z@{UB},  @{B}ö@{UB}, @{B}ä@{UB}, @{B}ü@{UB}, @{B}0@{UB}...@{B}9@{UB}, @{B}@@{UB},  @{B}§@{UB}, @{B}$@{UB}, @{B}'@{UB}, @{B} @{UB},  @{B}_@{UB}. You may not use  a
number as the first character.

   There are  two special  characters  which may  be used:  @{B}  @{UB} (tilde)  and  @{B}_@{UB}
(underscore). @{B}_@{UB} as  the first  character will create  a line  above the  name,
which is often used in mathematics. Inside  the name @{B}_@{UB} will create an index  -
characters after @{B}_@{UB} will  be used as  the index at  the bottom of  the name. @{B}  @{UB}
works similar, but creates an index at the  top of the name. You can use  both
kinds of indeces together. E.g. @{B}_a@{UB}, @{B}a_1@{UB}, @{B}a 1@{UB} or everything at once @{B}_a 2_1@{UB}.

   Starting with version 0.3  Laplace support the usage  of Greek symbols.  If
the name or an index matches the name  of a Greek letter, then this letter  is
used to  display  the  variable.  Number may  follow  the  letter  name.  E.g.
@{B}alpha1_beta@{UB}. A name  in lower  case represents a  small Greek  letter; if  the
first character of the name  is uppercase, then you  get an big Greek  letter.
All supported names are :

                alpha    Alpha    beta      Beta      chi     Ch
                delta    Delta    epsilon   Epsilon   eta     Eta
                gamma    Gamma    jota      Jota      kappa   Kappa
                lambda   Lambda   my        My        ny      Ny
                omega    Omega    omikron   Omikron   phi     Phi
                pi       Pi       psi       Psi       rho     Rho
                sigma    Sigma    tau       Tau       theta   Theta
                xi       Xi       ypsilon   Ypsilon   zeta    Zeta

   This list can be configured (see @{"preferences" LINK "Usage.guide/Preferences"}). You can add your own symbols
or just use another font for greek letters.



   An astonishing new feature is the possibility to use the result of any  ex-
pression as the reference name or as a  part of it. If you enclose an  expres-
sion in reverse apostrophes  @{B}`@{UB}, it will be  evaluated and the result  replaces
the expression. The only limitation is, that the result must be

 @{B}·@{UB} a string that contains only characters that are allowed for identifiers.
 @{B}·@{UB} a positive, integer
 @{B}·@{UB} empty. In that case there will be simply nothing inserted.

   Here is an example of it:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = 2;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} B_`a` = 1;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}B_2 = 1@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = ''alpha'';
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} B~`a`_`2+3` = 1;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}B~alpha_5 = 1@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a_0 = 12; a_1 = 5; a_2 = 16;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} for ( i = 0, i < 3, i += 1 ) result( a_`i` );
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}12@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}5@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}16@{UI}

   As you can see, you  can use an arbitrary  number of subexpression in  each
identifier.

@{U}Definition types@{UU}

   There are three difference kinds of definitions:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}Variables@{UB} - When  you reference a  @{B}variable@{UB}, it's contents  will be  in-
   serted. Variable are defined using @{I}name = expression @{UI}. E.g.
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a=3 @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a+1 @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}4@{UI}

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}Parameters@{UB} - A reference to a  @{B}parameter@{UB} will not be evaluated, it  will
   remain in the result. Use @{I}name := expression @{UI} to create a parameter. If
   you want to get the final result use the @{"xparm()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-XPARM"} function. E.g.
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a:=3 @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} 2*(a+2) @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}2*a+4@{UI}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} xparm(2*(a+2)) @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}10@{UI}

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}Constants@{UB} have  no value,  so  they won't  be  evaluate, even  with  the
   @{"xparm()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-XPARM"} function. They are defined using the @{B}const@{UB} keyword. E.g.
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} const a @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} 2*(a+2) @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}2*a+4@{UI}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} xparm(2*(a+2)) @{B}<return>@{UB}
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}2*a+4@{UI}

   You can  also define  @{B}functions@{UB}. Just  enter a  argument list  embedded  in
bracket after the object name, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x)=x^3 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} g(x,y):=sqrt(x^2+y^2) @{B}<return>@{UB}

   When referencing a  function you have  to specify the  arguments to be  in-
serted into the function's expression, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(3) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}27@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} const a @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(a+1) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}(a+1)^3@{UI}

   It is also possible to omit the  arguments; if you do so, Laplace will  in-
sert the arguments as they were defined, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f'(x,y) = derive(f(x,y),x) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f'(x,y) = derive(f,x) @{B}<return>@{UB}

   Note that the last two lines are the  same, because @{I}f @{UI} will be expanded to
@{I}f(x,y) @{UI}.

@{U}Quick arithmetics@{UU}

   Similar to the C language Laplace  knows some abbreviations for often  used
expression. Instead of writing
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = a + 2;

   you should use
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a += 2;

   This is faster than the first form, because Laplace can make some  internal
optimizations. This works for the following binary operators:

                           @{B}x += a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x + a@{UB}
                           @{B}x -= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x - a@{UB}
                           @{B}x *= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x * a@{UB}
                           @{B}x /= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x / a@{UB}
                          @{B}x ||= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x || a@{UB}
                          @{B}x or= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x || a@{UB}
                          @{B}x &&= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x && a@{UB}
                         @{B}x and= a@{UB}   <=>   @{B}x = x && a@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Types"
@TITLE "Types"
@NEXT "Loops"
@PREV "References"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------------- Types -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "Types"
@{U}7.4) Types@{UU}

   Each expression has a type. Laplace supports a complex hierarchy of types:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{"invalid" LINK "TYPE-INVALID"}
 @{B}·@{UB} @{"identifier" LINK "TYPE-IDENTIFIER"}
 @{B}·@{UB} @{"object" LINK "TYPE-OBJECT"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"number" LINK "TYPE-NUMBER"}
       @{B}·@{UB} @{"real" LINK "TYPE-REAL"}
          @{B}·@{UB} @{"integer" LINK "TYPE-INTEGER"}
             @{B}·@{UB} @{"posinteger" LINK "TYPE-POSINTEGER"}
             @{B}·@{UB} @{"neginteger" LINK "TYPE-NEGINTEGER"}
       @{B}·@{UB} @{"complex" LINK "TYPE-COMPLEX"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"tensor" LINK "TYPE-TENSOR"}
       @{B}·@{UB} @{"vector" LINK "TYPE-VECTOR"}
       @{B}·@{UB} @{"matrix" LINK "TYPE-MATRIX"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"array" LINK "TYPE-ARRAY"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"boolean" LINK "TYPE-BOOLEAN"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"string" LINK "TYPE-STRING"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"equation" LINK "TYPE-EQUATION"}
    @{B}·@{UB} @{"interval" LINK "TYPE-RANGE"}

   You can query the type of an object with the @{"typeof()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-TYPEOF"} function. It  returns
a string with the object's type. To check, if an object is of a given type  or
a subclass of that  type, use @{"issubtype()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-ISSUBTYPE"}, which  returns boolean. The  vector
@{I}[1,2] @{UI} for example has a type of @{B}vector@{UB}, which is a subclass of @{B}tensor@{UB} and @{B}ob-@{UB}
@{B}ject@{UB}.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} v = [1,2]
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} typeof(v)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}"vector"@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} issubtype(v, "vector")
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}TRUE@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} issubtype(v, "tensor")
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}TRUE@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} issubtype(v, "object")
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}TRUE@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} issubtype(v, "array")
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}FALSE@{UI}

   A variable declaration is a type name followed by the variable's name.  Ad-
ditionally to the type name, you can set some special attributes:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}const@{UB} - A constant object of the  given type is created. You cannot  as-
   sign a value to a constant.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}numeric@{UB} - not implemented.

   Laplace recognizes a declaration, when it encounters a type name or one  of
the attributes. If you use an attribute, you may omit the type name, which  is
@{B}number@{UB} by default. Without attributes, you must give the type name,  otherwise
the declaration won't be recognized.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} number a;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = 1;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} const vector a;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} const a;


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-INVALID"
@TITLE "type 'invalid'"
@NEXT "TYPE-IDENTIFIER"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------- type 'invalid' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'invalid'"
@{U}Type @{B}invalid@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}invalid@{UB} is not a real  type, but is assigned  to every object that  doesn't
have a valid type. For example @{I}det(2) @{UI}  has the type @{B}invalid@{UB}, because you can
calculate the determinant only for matrices.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-IDENTIFIER"
@TITLE "type 'identifier'"
@NEXT "TYPE-OBJECT"
@PREV "TYPE-INVALID"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------- type 'identifier' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'identifier'"
@{U}Type @{B}identifier@{UB}@{UU}

   Currently it doesn't make  sense to declare an  object of type  @{B}identifier@{UB}.
But you might get an  error message telling you,  that a function expected  an
object of type @{B}identifier@{UB} as an  argument, e.g. the @{"derive()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-DERIVE"} function, if  you
only give one argument. This means that you have to pass the name of a  previ-
ously declared object as the argument.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} derive(x^2)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}ERROR@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x) = x^2
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} derive(f)


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-OBJECT"
@TITLE "type 'object'"
@NEXT "TYPE-NUMBER"
@PREV "TYPE-IDENTIFIER"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------- type 'object' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'object'"
@{U}Type @{B}object@{UB}@{UU}

   This is the base type for all  usually used types. An expression is  either
@{B}invalid@{UB} or has a sub type of @{B}object@{UB}.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-NUMBER"
@TITLE "type 'number'"
@NEXT "TYPE-REAL"
@PREV "TYPE-OBJECT"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------- type 'number' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'number'"
@{U}Type @{B}number@{UB}@{UU}

   These are just numbers as we all know them (or do we know them all?!).

   Numbers can be entered in exponential style, which is
             @{B}{+/-/<nothing>}ddddd[.ddddd][e{+/-/<nothing>}dddd]@{UB}.
   Ufff, but  it's  quite  easy;-)  to  enter  e.g.  @{B}6.626  *  10^(-34)@{UB}  write
@{B}6.626e-34@{UB}. The  (whole)  number  after  @{B}e@{UB} is  just  the  exponent.  Don't  use
brackets, if the exponent is negative!

   Laplace supports complex numbers. To  enter a complex number, simply  write
something  like  @{I}1  +  2@{UI}i@{I}  @{UI}.   But  they  are  not  fully  implemented,   e.g.
error-distribution doesn't work correctly when you have complex values in your
expression and not all functions work with complex arguments.

   As long as you enter only whole numbers, Laplace tries to use fractions, so
enter @{B}1/2@{UB} instead of @{B}0.5@{UB} (in this simple case Laplace converts @{B}0.5@{UB} to @{B}1/2@{UB}  it-
self, but this may not  always work). This way you  can enter things like  @{B}1/7@{UB}
exactly, and you won't get result which are almost exact zero, when it  should
be exact ;-)

   A fantastic  new feature  of  Laplace is  the  direct support  of  Gaussian
error-distribution. Now it is possible to enter values with their standard er-
ror, do what ever calculations  you have to do, and  then get the result  with
the correct error value! This is very useful, if you are calculating with  re-
sult of some measurements, like I did during my physical practical.

   For example, you want  to measure the earth  acceleration by measuring  the
falling time of a ball. You measured the falling height to 1.119 meters with a
precision of one millimeter and the time  to 0.50 seconds with a precision  of
1/50 second. Now simply enter:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} t=0.50±0.02
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} h=1.119±0.001
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} g=2*s/h^2

   and that's all!! (Next time you should do it more precisely..)

   The @{B}±@{UB}  can be  entered  by @{B}alt-y@{UB}  (on the  German  keyboard) or  @{B}alt-z@{UB}  (on
others).

   But you should be aware, that in some cases you might get wrong result, be-
cause @{I}10±1*10±1 @{UI} is not the same as @{I}10±1  ^ 2 @{UI}. So, if the same value is  used
at different places in a formula, it  is evaluated as if they had  independent
error ranges!

   The best way to avoid this, is declaring all values with errors as  parame-
ters, construct your (possibly big) formula and simplify it, so that every pa-
rameter occurs only a single time, e.g.:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} x := 10±1
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} y := 12±2
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = 3*x^2*y^3
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} b = 5*x^3*y^2
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} result = a/b
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} xparm(result)

   If you on the other hand have something like this:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} x := 10±1
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} result = x/(x+1)

   you'll get a wrong error value and there is no way to avoid it, sorry.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-REAL"
@TITLE "type 'real'"
@NEXT "TYPE-INTEGER"
@PREV "TYPE-NUMBER"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------- type 'real' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'real'"
@{U}Type @{B}real@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}real@{UB} is a sub-type  of @{B}number@{UB}, specifying  numbers without imaginary  part,
e.g. @{B}5.34@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-INTEGER"
@TITLE "type 'integer'"
@NEXT "TYPE-POSINTEGER"
@PREV "TYPE-REAL"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------- type 'integer' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'integer'"
@{U}Type @{B}integer@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}integer@{UB} is a sub-type of @{B}real@{UB}, specifying real, whole numbers, e.g. @{B}-3@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-POSINTEGER"
@TITLE "type 'posinteger'"
@NEXT "TYPE-NEGINTEGER"
@PREV "TYPE-INTEGER"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------- type 'posinteger' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'posinteger'"
@{U}Type @{B}posinteger@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}posinteger@{UB} is a sub-type of @{B}integer@{UB}, specifying real, whole numbers  bigger
than zero, e.g. @{B}7@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-NEGINTEGER"
@TITLE "type 'neginteger'"
@NEXT "TYPE-COMPLEX"
@PREV "TYPE-POSINTEGER"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------- type 'neginteger' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'neginteger'"
@{U}Type @{B}neginteger@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}neginteger@{UB} is a sub-type of @{B}integer@{UB}, specifying real, whole numbers smaller
than zero, e.g. @{B}-9@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-COMPLEX"
@TITLE "type 'complex'"
@NEXT "TYPE-TENSOR"
@PREV "TYPE-NEGINTEGER"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------- type 'complex' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'complex'"
@{U}Type @{B}complex@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}complex@{UB} is a sub-type of @{B}number@{UB}, specifying numbers without real part, e.g.
@{B}3.5i@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-TENSOR"
@TITLE "type 'tensor'"
@NEXT "TYPE-VECTOR"
@PREV "TYPE-COMPLEX"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------- type 'tensor' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'tensor'"
@{U}Type @{B}tensor@{UB}@{UU}

   @{B}tensor@{UB} is the base type for @{B}vectors@{UB} and @{B}matrices@{UB}. A @{B}tensor@{UB} is a  orthogonal
arrangement of @{B}numbers@{UB} of @{I}n @{UI}  dimensions. @{I}n = 1 @{UI}  is a linear arrangement and
therefore a @{B}vector@{UB}. @{I}n = 2 @{UI} specifies  a square arragement of @{B}numbers@{UB} and is a
@{B}matrix@{UB}.

   To access single members  of a @{B}tensor@{UB}, write  the index in square  brackets
right after the tensor @{I}T[a,b,...] @{UI}. The index must have exactly @{I}n @{UI} components,
and numbering of the members starts at @{I}1 @{UI}.

   You can also access sub-tensors by  using @{B}intervals@{UB} in the index. @{I}T[2..4]  @{UI}
constructs a one  dimensinal tensor from  the one dimensional  tensor @{I}T @{UI}  with
three members @{I}2 @{UI}, @{I}3 @{UI}, @{I}4 @{UI}. @{I}T[2..4,2] @{UI}  is again a one dimensional tensor, this
time constructed  from a  two dimension  tensor @{I}T  @{UI} taking  the three  members
@{I}[2,2] @{UI}, @{I}[3,2] @{UI}, @{I}[4,2] @{UI}.  @{I}T[2..4,1..2] @{UI} creates a  two dimensional tensor with
the members @{I}[2,1] @{UI}, @{I}[3,1] @{UI}, @{I}[4,1] @{UI}, @{I}[2,2] @{UI}, @{I}[3,2] @{UI}, @{I}[4,2] @{UI}.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-VECTOR"
@TITLE "type 'vector'"
@NEXT "TYPE-MATRIX"
@PREV "TYPE-TENSOR"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------- type 'vector' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'vector'"
@{U}Type @{B}vector@{UB}@{UU}

   A vector is a tuple of numbers. To create the vector @{B}(2,4,1)@{UB} enter @{B}[2,4,1]@{UB}.
Any expression can be (of course) a component of a vector.

   You can add and multiply (scalar) two vectors, or multiply a @{B}number@{UB} or  @{B}ma-@{UB}
@{B}trix@{UB} with a vector (in  this order, not @{I}vector*number  @{UI}!). You get the vector
product of two 3-dimensional vector by typing @{B}vector × vector@{UB}. The @{B}×@{UB} is not an
ordinary x, but can be entered by  @{B}alt-x@{UB} (on the German keyboard and  probably
all others, too).

   To access the @{I}n @{UI}-th member of a vector @{I}v @{UI} (which can be any expression that
evaluates into a vector), append the index in square brackets @{I}v[n] @{UI}. The first
member has the index one.

   You can also use an @{B}interval@{UB} @{I}a..b @{UI}  as the index, extracting a vector with
the members @{I}a @{UI}  to @{I}b @{UI}. @{I}-infty  @{UI} as the  lower limit is replaced  by @{I}1 @{UI}, while
@{I}infty @{UI} as the upper limit is replaced by the dimension of the vector. This way
@{I}v[2..] @{UI} will replicate the vector @{I}v @{UI} without the first element.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-MATRIX"
@TITLE "type 'matrix'"
@NEXT "TYPE-ARRAY"
@PREV "TYPE-VECTOR"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------- type 'matrix' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'matrix'"
@{U}Type @{B}matrix@{UB}@{UU}

   The matrix with the row vectors @{B}(1,2,3)@{UB}, @{B}(4,5,6)@{UB} and @{B}(7,8,9)@{UB} can be created
with  @{B}[1,2,3;4,5,6;7,8,9]@{UB}.   If  you   have  column   vector  in   mind,   use
@{B}[1,4,7;2,5,8;3,6,9]!@{UB} instead (append an @{I}exclamation mark @{UI}).

   You can add and multiply  two matrices, or multiply  a @{B}number@{UB} and a  matrix
(in this order, not @{I}matrix*number @{UI}!).

   To access the element  in the @{I}n  @{UI}-th row and @{I}m  @{UI}-th column of  a matrix @{I}M @{UI}
(which can be any expression that evaluates into a matrix), append the indeces
in square brackets @{I}M[n,m] @{UI}. The first row/column has the index one.

   By using an @{B}interval@{UB} in the index, you can access row or column vectors  of
the matrix: @{I}M[n,..] @{UI} extracts the @{I}n @{UI}-th row into a vector, while @{I}M[..,m] @{UI} com-
poses a vector out of the @{I}m @{UI}-th column. The resulting vectors are always col-
umn vectors.

   With two @{B}intervals@{UB} you can extract a sub-matrix, e.g. to get the matrix @{I}N @{UI}
from a  matrix @{I}M  @{UI}, leaving  out the  first row  and the  first column,  write
@{I}N = M[2..,2..] @{UI}.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-ARRAY"
@TITLE "type 'array'"
@NEXT "TYPE-BOOLEAN"
@PREV "TYPE-MATRIX"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ---------------------------------------------- type 'array' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'array'"
@{U}Type @{B}array@{UB}@{UU}

   To create a array use the @{B}array()@{UB} command.

   A array is a collection of objects of the any type. Members can occur  mul-
tiple times in an array.

   If you calculate with array, all operations (except those affecting the ar-
ray directly) are applied to all members of the array, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} A=array(1,2,3) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} A+2 @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}{3,4,5}@{UI}

   The function @{"count()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-COUNT"} returns the number  of members in an array. To  access
the @{I}n @{UI}-th member of an array @{I}A @{UI} (which can be any expression, which evaluates
to an array), write the index in square brackets right after the array: @{I}A[n] @{UI}.
The first member has the index 1. If  you use an @{B}interval@{UB} @{I}a..b @{UI} as the index,
this creates a new array with  the members, taking the members  @{I}a @{UI} to @{I}b @{UI} from
@{I}A @{UI}.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} A=array(5,7,12,7) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} A[1] @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}5@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} (2*A)[2] @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}14@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} A[2..3] @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}    => @{I}[7,12]@{UI}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-BOOLEAN"
@TITLE "type 'boolean'"
@NEXT "TYPE-STRING"
@PREV "TYPE-ARRAY"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------- type 'boolean' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'boolean'"
@{U}Type @{B}boolean@{UB}@{UU}

   A boolean object can only contain the two values @{B}TRUE@{UB} and @{B}FALSE@{UB}.

   Possible operation for boolean objects are: @{B}&&@{UB} (and), @{B}||@{UB} (or), @{B}!&&@{UB}  (nand),
@{B}!||@{UB} (nor), @{B}^^@{UB} (xor) and @{B}!@{UB} (not).

@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a=TRUE
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} b=FALSE
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} c=TRUE
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a && (b || !c)


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-STRING"
@TITLE "type 'string'"
@NEXT "TYPE-EQUATION"
@PREV "TYPE-BOOLEAN"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------- type 'string' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'string'"
@{U}Type @{B}string@{UB}@{UU}

   Strings are surrounded by double quotes @{B}"@{UB}.

   Similar to strings in C, you can use the backslash @{B}\@{UB}\ as an escape character
to insert special characters to a string:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}\\" @{UB} - add  a double quote  (otherwise you'd get  problems with the  sur-
   rounding quotes!).
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}\\n @{UB} - add a new line (ASCII code 10).
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}\\\\ @{UB} - the backslash itself.

   To concatenate two strings, simply @{I}add @{UI} them:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} " Hi " + " there!"
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}" Hi there!"@{UI}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-EQUATION"
@TITLE "type 'equation'"
@NEXT "TYPE-RANGE"
@PREV "TYPE-STRING"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------- type 'equation' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'equation'"
@{U}Type @{B}equation@{UB}@{UU}

   An equation is created by the @{B}=?@{UB} operator.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} E= 2*x+4 =? 0 @{B}<return>@{UB}

   To access the left or  right hand side of a  given equation, use the  func-
tions @{"lhs()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-LHS"} or @{"rhs()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-RHS"}.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} lhs(E) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}2*x+4@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} rhs(E) @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}0@{UI}

   You can of course calculate with equations. The operations will be  applied
on both side of the equation.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} E= 2*x+4 =? 0
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} E= E-4
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} E= E/2

   You can also apply functions line @{B}sin()@{UB}, @{B}exp()@{UB}... on equations, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} E= ln(x) =? 12*e @{B}<return>@{UB}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} E=exp(E) @{B}<return>@{UB}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TYPE-RANGE"
@TITLE "type 'interval'"
@PREV "TYPE-EQUATION"
@TOC "Types"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------- type 'interval' -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Types" "type 'interval'"
@{U}Type @{B}interval@{UB}@{UU}

   An @{B}interval@{UB} is a range of values, starting at @{I}a @{UI}, ending at @{I}b @{UI}, and is de-
fined by @{I}a..b @{UI}. @{I}a @{UI}  and @{I}b @{UI} can usually be  any @{B}number@{UB}, but there are  restric-
tions depending on the context the interval is used for. In most cases, @{I}a @{UI} and
@{I}b @{UI} have to be real numbers with @{B}a < b@{UB}.

   You may omit the lower and/or upper  limit of the range, which is than  re-
placed by @{I}-infty @{UI} respectively @{I}infty @{UI}.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Loops"
@TITLE "Loops"
@NEXT "Procedures"
@PREV "Types"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------------- Loops -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "Loops"
@{U}7.5) Loops@{UU}

   In contrast to most other statements, the loops won't return a result.

   You can always interrupt the loop using the @{"break()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-BREAK"} function.

@{U}the @{B}while@{UB}-statement@{UU}

   The statement or the block of statements following the @{B}while@{UB} keyword is ex-
ecuted as long as the argument evaluates to the boolean @{B}TRUE@{UB}.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = 0; b = 0;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} while ( a < 10 )
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} {
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   a += 1;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   b += irandom(10);
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} }

@{U}the @{B}for@{UB}-statement@{UU}

   The @{B}for@{UB}-loop is very close to the C @{B}for@{UB}-loop: the first argument is  evalu-
ated before the loop is started, the second on is a condition that is  checked
at the beginning of the loop and the third argument is evaluated at the end of
the loop.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} b = 0;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} for ( a = 0; a < 10; a += 1 )
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   b += irandom(10);


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Conditionals"
@TITLE "Conditionals"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ---------------------------------------------- Conditionals -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "" "Conditionals"
@{U}7.6) Conditionals@{UU}

   The @{B}if@{UB}-condition works exactly the way you  expect it to do: if the  condi-
tion is @{B}TRUE@{UB} the first statement or statement block is executed, otherwise the
@{B}else@{UB}-statement is executed, if there is one.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} if ( a > 5 )
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} {
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   b += 10;
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   c -= sin(b);
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} }
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} else
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   b -= 10;


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Procedures"
@TITLE "Procedures"
@NEXT "Options"
@PREV "Loops"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------------ Procedures -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "Procedures"
@{U}7.7) Procedures@{UU}

   The ability to create procedures is the most powerful invention of V0.8.

   The syntax for creating a  procedure is now very  similar to the syntax  of
the C language: The  return type of the  procedure, followed by an  identifier
with optional arguments and then a statement block:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} number foobar(number a)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} {
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}     if ( a > 0 )
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}         return(-1);
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}     else
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}         return(1);
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} }

   As you can see,  the @{"return()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-RETURN"}-functions, aborts  the procedure and  returns
the optional argument as the result of the procedure. If you omit the @{B}return()@{UB}
command, and the procedure reaches the end of the statement block, the  result
of the last expression is returned.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Options"
@TITLE "Options"
@PREV "Procedures"
@TOC "Syntax"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------------- Options -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Syntax" "Options"
@{U}7.8) Options@{UU}

   There are some options to influence  to calculation or presentation of  ex-
pressions. They can be used like any other reference, but they all start  with
a @{B}$@{UB} (dollar sign). You can assign a new value to it, just by typing e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $dispprec = 6
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = 3
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $dispprec = 2*a

or you can query the current value:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a = $dispprec
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}6@{UI}

   As always, Laplace searches  backwards until it finds  an option, this  way
setting an option will not influence  the lines above. If no explicit  assign-
ment has been done, the default value is used.

   These are the keyword:

 @{B}·@{UB}

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$convprec@{UB} - Default: @{B}14@{UB} - Possible  value: @{B}1..20@{UB}. Laplace tries to  con-
   vert floatpoints into  fractions whenever possible.  But the  floatpoint
   routines are not too exact, so there might be an small difference to the
   correct value (e.g. 1.2000000000000001  when it should  be 1.2). If  the
   difference is smaller than the  specified precision (precision 12  means
   10^(-12)), Laplace assumes the value as  a fraction and converts it  (in
   this case to  6/5). This is  not applied  to value near  zero, so  1e-30
   won't be converted to 0.

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$dispexp@{UB} - Default: @{B}6@{UB} - Possible  value: @{B}1..12@{UB}. Select number of  digits
   to be displayed before switching to exponential display.

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$dispprec@{UB} - Default: @{B}6@{UB} - Possible value: @{B}1..15@{UB}. Select maximum number of
   decimal digits to be displayed.

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$iref@{UB} - Default: @{B}TRUE@{UB}  - Possible value: @{B}TRUE@{UB},  @{B}FALSE@{UB}. The usage of  the
   single letter @{B}i@{UB} as a reference name can be somehow confusing. If you are
   working with complex numbers,  you probably mean @{B}i@{UB}  as @{B}sqrt(-1)@{UB}, but  in
   other cases you use @{B}i@{UB} as an index variable or something like that.
      If you set @{B}$iref@{UB} to @{B}TRUE@{UB}, @{B}i@{UB}  always stands for an reference, and  you
   have to enter @{B}1i@{UB}  to get the  complex number. Otherwise  @{B}i@{UB} means @{B}1i@{UB}  and
   there is no way to enter a  reference called @{B}i@{UB}. (Actually there is  one:
   @{B}`"i"`@{UB}, but this is a quite difficult way to enter a single letter...)

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$simplify@{UB} - Default: @{B}TRUE@{UB} - Possible value: @{B}TRUE@{UB}, @{B}FALSE@{UB}.  Enable/Disable
   simplification pass.  Without simplification,  the calculation  will  be
   faster, but the result might look quite ugly.

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$transpose@{UB} - Default: @{B}FALSE@{UB} - Possible  value: @{B}TRUE@{UB}, @{B}FALSE@{UB}. A matrix  is
   usually entered ordered by rows, similar to programs like MAPLE or  MAT-
   LAB. If you prefer column vectors, set this option to @{B}TRUE@{UB}.
      This  option  can  be  overwritten  be  entering  @{B}[..]~@{UB}  (always  use
   row-order) or @{B}[..]!@{UB} (always use column-order).

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$useerror@{UB} -  Default: @{B}TRUE@{UB}  - Possible  value: @{B}TRUE@{UB},  @{B}FALSE@{UB}. If  set  to
   @{B}FALSE@{UB}, Laplace will not use and display error ranges.

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}$usefloat@{UB} - Default:  @{B}FALSE@{UB} -  Possible value:  @{B}TRUE@{UB}, @{B}FALSE@{UB}.  If set  to
   @{B}TRUE@{UB}, Laplace will  always use  floatpoints and never  converts them  to
   fractions.

   For example:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $usefloat = FALSE
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} sin(2)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}sin(2)@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $usefloat = TRUE
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $dispprec = 5
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} sin(2)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}0.9093@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $dispprec = 8
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} sin(2)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}0.90929743@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a=12000.3
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $dispexp = 3
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}1.20003*10^ 4@{UI}
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} $dispexp = 6
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}   => @{I}12000.3@{UI}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ © by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
